00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 The topic about rationality is closely connected with the two aspects of our conference,The credo and the challenges of the future. First, the theme of the creed,which constitutes a rational expression of the faith of Christians.The creed is namely a written word explicitly and precisely articulated.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:50,000
 And second,I was originally invited to speak about the primacy in the church.However unconventional this may appear,what follows would be my contribution exactly to this topic about the primacy in the church.

3
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:19,000
 So,as a philosopher,I hold that it is not sufficient for a person merely to know the language,to be able to read and to write.We live in a culture that is literate enough to perform these basic tasks.Yet,everywhere around us,we encounter notorious forms of illiteracy.Fake news.

4
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 Conspiracy theories,Pseudoscience,superstition,etcetc.On one hand,we enjoy democracy,freedom of speech,and the right to participate in the political life of society.Freedom unprecedented in the history of the humankind.On the other hand,we observe a manifest incapacity for deeper insight

5
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 Into political realities,accompanied by mythological constructions of history,politics and society.Build upon mass propaganda and rudimentary emotionality.Pseudo-religiosity reigns through a legion of seemingly contradictory dog-side.In light of all this,I would pose one obvious question.

6
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:23,000
 How is it possible at this stage of human development that we live in such confusion?

7
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 As I mentioned earlier,it is not sufficient merely to be acquainted with the language.One must also be able to think the language.This may appear self-evident.Yet,in reality,it is far from the case.

8
00:02:41,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 The human being possesses a remarkable capacity to habitualize the actions it performs.Aristotle already speaks of this through his notion of hexis,or the Latina is formed habitus.Followed by Thomas Aquinas in the West,by Maximus the Confessor in the East,and even by the French sociologist Pierre Bourdieu in the 20th century.

9
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 What is subject to habitualization is not only virtue and vice,but also the very patterns of thought and reasoning.

10
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 To the point that one may effectively think without thinking.Paradoxical as it may sound,this is an apt description of the reality that surrounds us.We employ words without ever touching their meanings.

11
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 Just turn on the TV and listen to the way people speak about democracy.

12
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 European values, freedom or tradition,the fatherland or alternatively for the older generations,brotherhood and unity.

13
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:51,000
 these expressions are repeated so endlessly in public discourse in public discourse that no one any longer inquires into their meaning.

14
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 they appear self-evident while in fact they appear self-evident while in fact they are semantically empty.

15
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:16,000
 like the man in Christ's parable,from the man in Christ's parable from which an unclean spirit was cast out.

16
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 But because God the Logos did not enter in the spirit return in its former home with seven others more wicked than itself.

17
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 This I would argue is the perfect image of how illiteracy is the perfect image of how illiteracy is being expelled today.

18
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 The formerly literate mind of modern man is not inhabited by analytic and critical thought but left empty.

19
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 Into this void enters ignorance accompanied in this instance by the arrogance of those who have merely learned to read letters.

20
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 And click on their smartphones and their tablets.

21
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 In a similar manner theologians today skillfully employ complex formulations and engage with multi-layered topics.

22
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:27,000
 Such as in fact our own topic of primacy.

23
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 Without addressing the foundational layers of meaning.

24
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 Without which the superficial seemingly self-evident and apparently obvious layers cannot be properly understood.

25
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 The question of primacy is often reduced to whether a single bishop may hold a supreme position in the universal church.

26
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 And whether such primacy is merely a matter of honor or authority.

27
00:05:52,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 The content of notions like primacy remains very often to be obscured by the fog of self-evidence.

28
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 On this occasion I do not intend to analyze these terms in detail.

29
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 Rather I will focus on the foundational conceptual presuppositions from which one might approach the topic of the organization of Christ's church in the world and history.

30
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 In doing so I would examine whether it is possible to identify common starting points that might bring the perspectives of East and West closer together.

31
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 The fundamental evangelical presupposition of theological thought is contained in the opening verse of the gospel according to John.

32
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 In the beginning was the word or energy in a logos.

33
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 The polysemantic term logos in the Greek equivalent is the Greek equivalent of the Latin ratio.

34
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 From it derives the adjective logicos which denotes human rational capacity.

35
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:21,000
 It is symptomatic that contemporary neopatristic which has exerted a decisive influence on 20th century Orthodox theology categorically denies this meaning.

36
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 Attributing it entirely to Western theological rationalism which is just another ideology stripped of any substantive meaning.

37
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Instead it seeks to understand the logos as a mystical theological principle beyond human rational capacity signifying the God likeness inherent in created human nature.

38
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 This gives rise to a theological vision that tends to distance itself not only from Western thought but also from the ancient Hellenic philosophy from which the very terms and concepts it employs originally.

39
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 Notably such tendencies are particularly evident in contemporary in contemporary in some currents of contemporary Greek theology.

40
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 Instead the great church fathers of late antiquity and the Byzantine period strove to preserve as much as possible of the semantic content of the Greek terms received into the Christian tradition.

41
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 In other words the term logos never lost its rational dimension in Eastern thought.

42
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 Instead its primary meaning is assumed by Christ who gives meaning indeed its primary meaning is assumed by Christ who gives meaning to the other signified concepts.

43
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 But rationality was the rationality was at no point rejected as such.

44
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:08,000
 The division of a rational West and a mystical East is the product of the ideological reductionism of later epochs and in no way reflects the historical reality of Byzantine civilization and culture.

45
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 As an illustration for this we may consider the remarkable Byzantine philosopher Nicholas Kabasiles.

