139
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 Could be derived from the cited verse in the Gospel according to John.

140
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:34,000
 The word primacy understood in the sense of authority corresponds in ancient Greek to the term arche or archi and to its derived form archeotita.

141
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 The related term protosini, by contrast, has primarily a temporal meaning indicating precedence within a sequence of consecutive events.

142
00:11:50,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 The archi to which the Gospel of John refers does not simply signify the beginning of history, but designates the meta-temporal beginning of all that exists.

143
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 That is the divine eternity.

144
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 This beginning, prior to the beginning, determines the character of divine primacy.

145
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:28,000
 It transcends every human conception of primacy while simultaneously serving as the presupposition of every beginning within time, including the very time as such.

146
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:35,000
 By contrast, in the domain of history, one can speak of primacy through the categories of iconicity.

147
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:45,000
 The icon actively reflects the archetype it represents, without emulating it by essence.

148
00:12:45,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 In this case, the hypostasis of the divine logos is iconized in the innate logosity of humanity, which in the domain of created and contingent nature is manifested, namely as rationality.

149
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 The primacy of rationality in the domain of the Church's historical existence is determined by two coordinates, first, by adherence to the fundamental principle of Christian revelation and ecclesiastical tradition, and second, by consideration of the dynamics of historical reality.

150
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:48,000
 The primacy of reason in the life of the Church designates the capacity to manifest the absolute reality of the Kingdom of God through various forms of organization and activity, taking into account the prevailing intellectual, historical, and social circumstances.

151
00:13:48,000 --> 00:14:10,500
 In his book, the scaffolds of the Church, last year's conference participant, Dr. Kirill Hovorun, maintains that the various forms of church organization accumulated over its two millennium history are merely scaffolds attached over the centuries to the body of the Church.

152
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 He argues that one of those of these externally attached scaffolds, which are essentially distinct from the very nature of the Church, as he says, is its hierarchical structuring, which includes episcopal primacy.

153
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:48,320
 He interprets the famous 28th canon of the council of Halkedon precisely as an example showing that primacy is only a historical convenience, representing an administrative rather than a sacred institution.

154
00:14:48,320 --> 00:14:55,400
 Consequently, if we wish to speak about primacy in the immanent historical sense of the term,

155
00:14:55,400 --> 00:15:11,520
 We may need to shift the focus from the structures themselves understood as immutable, substantial realities, to the human faculty capable of constituting and transforming them.

156
00:15:11,520 --> 00:15:22,380
 Undoubtedly, this pertains to the rational faculty as the icon of the divine locus within the historical existence of man.

157
00:15:22,380 --> 00:15:31,780
 In this way, the question of primacy would be transferred into the domain of the dimension of ecclesial life in history.

158
00:15:31,780 --> 00:15:39,660
 Such a desubstantialization of the Church's structures is not some sort of postmodern invention,

159
00:15:39,660 --> 00:15:53,320
 But is fully faithful to the fundamental intuition of Byzantine metaphysics, which takes energy, rather than the substance, as the primary characteristic of being.

160
00:15:53,320 --> 00:16:04,300
 Moreover, its aim is not to abolish the structures, but rather to invoke the concluding words of Hovarun,

161
00:16:04,300 --> 00:16:10,760
 To keep them open, to keep them open, so that they can be readjusted to their original meaning.

162
00:16:10,760 --> 00:16:19,640
 In order to address the question of Christ's organization, the Church's organization in history,

163
00:16:19,640 --> 00:16:26,660
 It is first necessary to apprehend the fundamental principles, or logo, of ecclesiality.

164
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:31,400
 By the way, Hovarun names these principles the nature of the Church.

165
00:16:31,400 --> 00:16:36,560
 And I'm not fully convinced that this is the best terminological and conceptual solution.

166
00:16:36,560 --> 00:16:38,220
 But that is another discussion.

167
00:16:38,220 --> 00:16:46,320
 Further, it is essential to determine how these principles may be realized under the conditions in which we live,

168
00:16:46,460 --> 00:16:55,020
 Without losing sight of the two millennial experience that the contemporary Christian Church carries behind it.

169
00:16:55,020 --> 00:17:07,180
 To conclude, the question of primacy in the Church is simultaneously both a closed and an open one.

170
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:16,020
 On the one hand, absolute primacy belongs to Christ, who is the incarnate Word, Logos, of God.

171
00:17:16,020 --> 00:17:25,200
 On the other hand, the structuring of the Church in time remains a dynamic process until the end of the ages.

172
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:31,500
 Dynamic does not mean arbitrary in the sense of the extremes of liberal theology,

173
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:40,080
 Just as traditional does not imply being trapped in the patterns of the past, as in fundamentalist conservativism.

174
00:17:40,080 --> 00:17:48,000
 Dynamism implies dialogue, a term that inherently contains the term logos.

175
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:57,080
 This dialogue lies in the foundation of the discourse we refer to as Christian philosophy.

176
00:17:57,760 --> 00:18:04,640
 It involves all the imperfections characteristic of the contingent reality in which this dialogue takes place.

177
00:18:04,640 --> 00:18:14,920
 There are disagreements, disputes, misunderstandings, social influences, mutual condemnations, reconciliations, etc.

178
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:25,560
 Yet, it is precisely through this dialogue that the structures of the Church are being shaped throughout its history.

179
00:18:25,560 --> 00:18:35,300
 In this presentation, I do not aim to provide a definite answer to the question of primacy as approached from the Orthodox Christian philosophical perspective.

180
00:18:35,300 --> 00:18:47,620
 I believe such an ambiguous answer is impossible, at least if we wish to remain faithful to the evangelical principle of the absolute primacy of the Divine Logos within His Church.

181
00:18:47,620 --> 00:18:58,300
 However, I am convinced that the established coordinates can open pathways toward a new theological synthesis,

182
00:18:58,300 --> 00:19:07,460
 one that, consistent with the Nicene model, would hold universal significance for all of Christianity.

183
00:19:07,460 --> 00:19:08,780
 Thank you.

184
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:08,860
 Thank you.

185
00:19:08,860 --> 00:19:08,980
 Thank you.

